National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan gave a preview of the NATO Summit during the trip to Brussels. The main objective of the summit is to send a clear message that Article 5, which guarantees mutual defense, is a sacred guarantee. The United States regards NATO as the foundation for its security and will be there for its allies. The leaders will discuss a range of issues, including the drawdown in Afghanistan, cyber defense, emerging challenges posed by China, and the new Strategic Concept for NATO. There will also be discussions on Russia, including embassy presence in Afghanistan, security arrangements, and the S-400 air defense system in Turkey. The President will also meet with Baltic presidents and President Erdogan of Turkey to discuss various issues. The summit will address the security and military dimension of global challenges and emphasize the importance of democratic values.